Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — string ID vs full object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs (source)
[RelayCommand]
async Task OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass primitive query parameter
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass the full object via dictionary
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    });
}
```

**3. Receive on the target ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: primitive — value arrives as string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
            ProductId = idObj.ToString();

        // Approach B: complex object — value arrives as the original type
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var prodObj) && prodObj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation** | URI query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Received as** | `string` | Original CLR type |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (in-process only) |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, small values | Complex/nested objects |

> **Tip:** You can combine both in one call — pass the ID in the URI for deep-link support and the object in the dictionary as a cache to avoid a redundant fetch.
